Object classes indicate difficulty of containment, not inherent danger of the anomaly being contained. Yes, most Keter class objects are world-ending horrors, but not all. Some are just really, really hard to keep from breaking the masquerade.

That said, the object in question here isn't the remains of Pluto. It's the planetary-scale jellyfish, of which there are more eggs hanging out, waiting to hatch in the Kuiper belt. So we got lucky this time and it headed out for Barnard's Star. What happens when, say, Eris hatches and it strikes out for a different star at 30km/s and, oops, collides with the Earth? Just because the danger doesn't grab you by the face and scream your name, doesn't mean it isn't a potential threat.







